title: Ana Milán y el jersey estilo alpino que más calienta de Sfera
text:
No hay nada que sea más capaz de frenar el frío y quedarse congelada que un buen jersey bien grueso y calentito. De esos que te abrazan y reconfortan, capaces de calentar incluso el alma. Aunque debería ser una tarea fácil, lo cierto es que no. Las tendencias estos últimos meses han ido de cabeza enfocadas hacia las transparencias y los encajes, muy alejados del estar protegida y con calor frente al frío.
En la búsqueda insaciable de un buen jersey, de los de toda la vida, pero eliminando el detalle de que piquen, nos topamos con la última adquisición de Ana Milán, una joya que ha compartido en redes sociales y que ya hemos añadido a nuestro carrito de la compra.
El jersey calentito de Ana Milán Si por algo encanta el estilo de Ana Milán es por estar siempre a la última y descubrir los verdaderas joyas de las tiendas más top del momento. Ya sea por el buen rollo que genera o por ser una auténtica cazatesoros de la web, no podemos evitar querer recrear su armario al completo. Si te pasa como a nosotras y ya eres una fan declarada y consagrada de la actriz, te interesa saber todo sobre el jersey calentito y que no pica de Milán.
ana milán.PNG
Un jersey que las alternativas de Malasaña jurarían que es vintage. Se trata de un jersey de Sfera, uno de los más bonitos que hemos visto de estilo alpino. Un precioso color gris oscuro con detalles en la zona del cuello caja y pecho en dorado y blanco. Con este jersey nos imaginamos a los famosos de los ochenta tomando un chocolate caliente tras una dura jornada esquiando.
Si fuésemos tú, no tardaríamos mucho en en ir a la web de Sfera y hacerte con el tuyo (o su alternativa camel) porque seguro que vuelan en cuestión de segundos.

author: Connielove Mawutornyo Dzodzegbe
title: Why is the price control L.I for cement only? – John Gatsi quizzes
text:
The Dean of the University of Cape Coast Business School, Prof John Gatsi, is questioning the rationale behind establishing a legislative instrument specifically aimed at regulating cement prices, a single commodity within the construction industry.
According to him, if the government genuinely intends to enhance the industry, it should implement regulations comprehensively for all commodities, not just cement.
Speaking on JoyFM’s Top Story on Thursday, June 27, he asked, “Why only cement? If it is the right thing to do, then we don’t use only cement for construction, you use other materials which are also very sensitive to price development in the country.”
His comments follows Trades and Industry Minister, KT Hammond’s pledge to disregard a petition from the Chamber of Cement Manufacturers to delay the implementation of a legislative instrument aimed at regulating cement prices.
Read also : Bill to regulate cement prices will be laid, passed before Parliament adjourns – Trade Minister KT Hammond insists that the law is essential to prevent a cartel of manufacturers from exploiting the public.
Under the proposed LI, cement manufacturers could face up to three years in jail for violations.
However, the Dean of the Business School warned that this approach might potentially impact the economy negatively.
“If we are not careful, we will get to a point that items which are sensitive to prices will be drawn under price control and that will not be the best for the economy,” he said.
Also on the same show, Ranking Member of the Trade, Industry and Tourism Committee, Yusif Sulemana, said that the approach was temporary and not a solution to checking inflation in the housing sector.
He argued that various raw materials are assembled to produce cement, and if the government insists on regulating the price, the standard of cement might be compromised.
Meanwhile, the Ghana Real Estate Developers Association says the legislative instrument aimed at regulating cement prices in the country was a step in the right direction.
Read also : Minority to oppose new L.I. seeking to regulate prices of cement The Minority in Parliament has voiced strong opposition to the proposed Legislative Instrument . Minority Spokesperson on Legal and Constitutional Affairs, Bernard Ahiafor stated that the regulation contradicts the parent act, which covers standards for all goods and services.
“The parent act by its objects deals with all goods and services, that is setting the standard for all goods and services including the cement, and the understanding of the standard is controlling the quality of all goods and services produced and imported in the country.”
According to the spokesperson, the GSA is responsible for setting quality standards, not controlling prices.
He stated that selling is different from pricing of goods and services.
“We are of the view that if the LI is allowed to pass through parliament which will set the price of cement, then equally all goods and services produced in the country must go through price control because you cannot single out only cement when the parent law is dealing with all goods and services.”
According to Mr Ahiafor, there are domestic remedies which should be used to address these concerns instead of resorting to legal action.

author: Matt Phillips
title: Missing teen found in Tangipahoa Parish; former Jennings resident arrested
text:
TANGIPAHOA PARISH, La. (KPLC) - A former Jennings resident is accused of bringing a 14-year-old runaway from Tennessee to Louisiana and having sex with her.
The girl has been found safe and Alexander Materne, 28, of St. Rose, Louisiana has been arrested.
Andrew Materne, 28, is accused of taking a 14-year-old runaway from her home in Tennessee to his home in Louisiana. (Tangipahoa Parish Sheriff's Office) According to a news release from the St. Charles Parish Sheriff’s Office , Materne met the girl while playing an online game, and made arrangements to pick her up from her home in Tennessee so she could stay with him.
On Dec. 23, the sheriff’s office said Materne brought the girl to his home in St. Rose and engaged in sexual acts. The sheriff’s office said the girl then disclosed her age to Materne.
After some time, Materne brought the girl to a secluded, wooded area in Tangipahoa Parish and left her with a tent, food, and water, the St. Charles Parish Sheriff’s Office said. Materne then went to Jennings to celebrate Christmas with his family.
On Christmas Eve, Jennings Police Chief Danny Semmes said his office received a call about Materne possibly having the girl in Jennings. However, when police went to check at the family home in Jennings, they were told he no longer lived there.
Semmes said that on Christmas morning, Jennings police were told Materne had returned to the family home and later made contact with him.
According to Jennings police , Materne told authorities he picked the girl up from her home in Tennessee and brought her to his home in St. Rose. Materne said he had sex with the girl before bringing her to the wooded area in Tangipahoa Parish, where she remained for about two days.
Semmes said Materne agreed to show investigators where the girl was, leading them to a tent in the woods 42 miles from his home.
The girl was found safe, taken to a hospital, and returned to her family, authorities said.
Materne was booked into the Tangipahoa Parish Jail for the following charges:
Aggravated kidnapping of a child Contributing to the delinquency of a juvenile Materne also faces arrest warrants for felony counts of human trafficking and carnal knowledge. According to the St. Charles Parish Sheriff’s Office, Materne will be booked into the parish jail once he can be transported.

title: Condenaron a 12 años de prisión a un cazador furtivo en Indonesia por matar rinocerontes de Java - Infobae
text:
La condena a Sunendi marca un hito en la protección de la fauna, mientras Indonesia refuerza la vigilancia en el Parque Nacional de Ujung Kulon - Getty Images Un tribunal en Indonesia ha condenado a Sunendi , un cazador furtivo, a 12 años de prisión por matar al menos seis rinocerontes de Java , una especie al borde de la extinción. Esta sentencia incluye una multa de 100 millones de rupias (6.140 dólares) por la matanza, conservación y comercialización de partes de estos animales protegidos.
“El acusado fue declarado culpable de matar, conservar y comercializar partes de animales silvestres protegidos”, afirmó el juez principal del tribunal de la provincia de Banten , en el este de Java. Sunendi, conocido únicamente por su nombre, fue hallado culpable de cometer estos crímenes entre 2019 y 2023 en el parque nacional de Ujung Kulon, al oeste de Java.
La sentencia se dio en un contexto donde el gobierno y la policía de Indonesia están investigando a un grupo que se cree responsable de la muerte de 26 rinocerontes de Java desde 2019 . Se estima que en estado salvaje solo quedan aproximadamente 82 ejemplares de esta especie, lo que las convierte en uno de los mamíferos más amenazados del planeta. Varios integrantes del grupo fueron detenidos en los últimos meses, y la búsqueda de otros ocho sospechosos continúa.
El gobierno indonesio intensifica la lucha contra la caza furtiva con patrullas y drones tras la condena de Sunendi, líder de una red de cazadores de rinocerontes - Getty Images Según las autoridades, Sunendi es uno de los líderes de una red de cazadores furtivos , quienes han matado y vendido partes de rinocerontes a precios elevados en el mercado negro. Las partes de estos animales, especialmente los cuernos , son muy buscadas en países como China , donde se usan para la elaboración de medicamentos y productos cosméticos.
Durante la operación que llevó a la captura de Sunendi, la policía encontró cabezas de rinocerontes cortadas y restos óseos de estos animales, evidentes pruebas del impacto devastador de la caza furtiva en la biodiversidad local. “El testigo Ujang Acep encontró la cabeza de un rinoceronte javanés o de un rinoceronte de un cuerno en junio de 2023 en la zona donde los rinocerontes de Java bebían y se bañaban”, reveló el juez Pandji Answinartha en el tribunal. Además, se recuperaron mapas y datos específicos sobre la distribución de los rinocerontes en el parque, que confirmó que la actividad de caza furtiva era meticulosamente planificada.
La organización de conservación Auriga Nusantara ha instado al gobierno a tratar el problema con la seriedad que requiere, al señalar que la matanza de 26 rinocerontes Javan en un período tan corto podría ser la más grande ocurrida en la historia reciente. La organización pidió “un castigo severo para los responsables como un disuasivo”, y destacó la urgente necesidad de preservar los pocos rinocerontes que quedan.
Sunendi, líder de una red de cazadores furtivos, recibió una condena de 12 años de prisión por matar rinocerontes de Java; continúa la búsqueda de más sospechosos - Getty Images Para salvaguardar la especie, el Ministerio de Medio Ambiente y Bosques de Indonesia, dirigido por Satyawan Pudyatmoko , ha implementado medidas adicionales. Estas incluyen patrullas de 24 horas en el parque, el uso de drones térmicos para detectar intrusos y la colaboración con las fuerzas armadas y la policía para realizar arrestos. “Hemos cambiado nuestra estrategia de conservación hacia un sistema de protección completa, donde ninguna persona puede ingresar al área del parque sin una razón justificada” explicó Pudyatmoko.
Indonesia también está considerando reformas legales para aumentar las sanciones contra la caza furtiva. Actualmente, la pena máxima por este delito es de cinco años de prisión , pero se busca que las nuevas sanciones sean más severas para generar un mayor efecto disuasorio.
El caso de Sunendi marca un hito en la lucha contra la caza furtiva, pero también resalta la necesidad continua de esfuerzos concertados para proteger a las especies en peligro de extinción. Con la esperanza de que estas medidas estructurales y legales puedan mitigar la amenaza y garantizar un futuro más seguro para los rinocerontes de Java, queda patente que la protección de la vida silvestre es una tarea constante y desafiante.

author: @KMOV
title: St. Louis war hero recognized as one of 40 elite ‘thieves’ in bloody WWII battle
text: St. Louis war hero recognized as one of 40 elite ‘thieves’ in bloody WWII battle Cpl. Richard Knoll fought during WWII’s Battle of Saipan alongside other elite Scout-Snipers, a.k.a. ‘thieves.’ ST. LOUIS, Mo. (First Alert 4) - At Jefferson Barracks National Cemetery in St. Louis, John Knoll visited his father’s grave Thursday and paid his respects. “I try to get out here at least once a year,” Knoll said about his father. “I miss him. He was my hero.” Cpl. Richard Knoll was a World War II veteran but also a ‘thief’ - a legacy his family learned more about after losing their father to cancer in 2006. “He didn’t talk about [his time overseas] much,” Knoll recounted about his father. “I know he dealt with PTSD.” As a ‘thief,’ these marines were some of the toughest fighters, according to Wisconsin-based author Joseph Tachovsky. Tachovsky knows because his father led the elite platoon of World War II Marine Scout-Snipers. Lt. Frank Tachovsky’s ‘40 thieves’ broke all rules, Tachovsky said. Cpl. Knoll was one of them. “They were trained to live and work behind enemy lines for days at a time,” Tachovsky said. “These were the elite of the elite, the toughest of the tough. They had to be. They were trained in silent killing techniques, and they learned key Japanese phrases.” Their training came in handy during the 1944 [Battle of Saipan,](https://www.nps.gov/amme/learn/historyculture/battle-of-saipan.htm) known as one of the war’s bloodiest battles. The fight resulted in the American occupation of the Japanese island of Saipan, located in the Pacific Ocean, putting the Japanese home islands within the range of U.S. Army bombers. Despite being honorable and ultimately successful fighters, Tachovsky said the Marines were the poorest-equipped of the armed forces, using repurposed weapons, rations and uniforms from World War I. “So, they stole,” Tachovsky said, “mostly because they had to. Weapons, food, anything they could find in Army and Navy storage depots. Even from enemies.” Tachovsky now visits the families and graves of the men his father led during the Battle of Saipan. Several of the ‘thieves’ are from the midwest, including from St. Louis and Kansas City. A eulogy read at his own father’s funeral in 2011 sparked a curiosity that pulled him in every direction across the country, as well as into his own father’s archives. “For about a year or two, I just traveled around the United States tracking down and interviewing the surviving members of [my father’s] platoon,” Tachovsky said. His travels brought him to St. Louis, where he met Knoll. “We’ve met in person twice, and I’ve visited his father’s grave three times because I couldn’t find [the family] at first,” Tachovsky said. The uncovering of history inspired Tachovsky to write the book [40 Thieves on Saipan: The Elite Marine Scout-Snipers in One of WWII’s Bloodiest Battles](https://militaryhistorynow.com/2020/06/04/the-40-thieves-of-saipan-meet-the-elite-marine-scout-snipers-of-the-pacific-war/#google_vignette), documenting the lives and legacies of the ‘thieves’ who fought in World War II. The chapters detail the daily trials and tribulations of the war heroes, while also filling in the gaps for the family and children of the ‘40 thieves,’ who may not have ever known there was more to the stories they had been told. “History is still writing itself. I feel like I’m always learning something new,” Tachovsky said. “I just learned a few months ago the movie ‘Ali Baba and the 40 Thieves’ came out in January of 1944. That also inspired the name ‘40 thieves’ for the platoon.” “Our fathers and what they did -- I can’t imagine being 20 years old and going into war 3000 miles away,” Knoll said. “I’m sure he had to do things he’s not proud of ... but I’m proud of him.” While the ‘thieves’ had to commit the “unspeakable,” according to Tachovsky, the U.S. would not have won the war had they not. “Nothing but respect,” Knoll said. Cpl. Richard Knoll was laid to rest in 2006 at Jefferson Barracks National Cemetery in St. Louis. Copyright 2024 KMOV. All rights reserved.

author: Pacific Daily News
title: NWS: High risk of rip currents, small craft advisory through the weekend | News | guampdn.com
text: The National Weather Service Guam Weather Forecast Office said that a high risk of rip currents will be in effect for Guam, Rota, Tinian, and Saipan from 6 p.m. Friday to Sunday night for east-facing reefs of the Marianas. Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away from the shore into deeper water. Inexperienced swimmers should remain out of the water due to dangerous conditions. If caught in a rip current, do not swim against the current. Swim in a direction following the shoreline, face the shore and call or wave for help, NWS said. A small craft advisory will be in effect for Guam, Rota, Tinian, and Saipan from 6 p.m. Friday until 5 p.m. on Sunday. Northeast winds of 15 to 25 knots, with gusts up to 30 knots, and seas of 7 to 11 feet are expected. Inexperienced mariners, especially those operating smaller vessels, should avoid boating in hazardous conditions. The Offices of Guam Homeland Security and Civil Defense remind the community to avoid hazardous surf and seas. Visit the following links for the latest advisory information: - NWS Website: [https://www.weather.gov/gum/](https://www.weather.gov/gum/) - NWS Facebook: [https://www.facebook.com/NWSGuam/](https://www.facebook.com/NWSGuam/) - GHS/OCD Website: [https://ghs.guam.gov/](https://ghs.guam.gov/) - GHS/OCD Facebook: [https://www.facebook.com/GHSOCD/](https://www.facebook.com/GHSOCD/)
